  "body": "This PR adds a simple `__call__` method to the gradient explainer. As of now, the `__call__` method on a gradient explainer raises to the following exception for me:\r\n```\r\nTraceback (most recent call last):\r\n  File \"<string>\", line 1, in <module>\r\n  File \"/Users/nico/.pyenv/versions/3.9.9/envs/ml-autocuration/lib/python3.9/site-packages/shap/explainers/_explainer.py\", line 210, in __call__\r\n    if issubclass(type(self.masker), maskers.OutputComposite) and len(args)==2:\r\nAttributeError: 'Gradient' object has no attribute 'masker'\r\n```\r\nAdding a `__call__` method would allow a more unified interface between explainers, following the examples in the README. notably, it allows the creation of beeswarm plots for Gradient explainers with the usual syntax:\r\n```\r\nexplainer = shap.GradientExplainer(classifier, background)\r\nshap_values = explainer(x)\r\nshap.plots.beeswarm(shap_values)\r\n```\r\nas opposed to having to explicitly create an Explanation object with, e.g.,\r\n```    \r\nshap_values = explainer.shap_values(x)[0]\r\nexplanation = Explanation(values=shap_values, data=x, feature_names=feature_names)\r\nshap.plots.beeswarm(explanation)\r\n```\r\n\r\nI've run the tests locally and they pass.",
